### 3. Timing Checks
Debuggers (especially when single-stepping) introduce significant latency. By measuring the time it takes to execute a set of instructions, a program can infer if a debugger is slowing it down.

#### `RDTSC` (Read Time-Stamp Counter)
The `RDTSC` instruction returns the current processor cycle count. By calling it before and after a standard operation, you can check if the elapsed cycles exceed a reasonable threshold.

```cpp
#include <intrin.h>

void CheckRDTSC() {
    unsigned __int64 t1 = __rdtsc();

    // Perform a trivial operation
    int x = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
        x += i;
    }

    unsigned __int64 t2 = __rdtsc();
    unsigned __int64 delta = t2 - t1;

    // Threshold depends on CPU speed, but 1,000,000 cycles is usually too long for a simple loop
    if (delta > 1000000) {
        std::cout << "[+] Debugger detected via RDTSC timing check!" << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "[-] No debugger detected via RDTSC." << std::endl;
    }
}
```

### 4. Exception-Based Checks
Debuggers handle exceptions differently than the operating system does. By intentionally triggering an exception, a program can observe who handles it.

#### `INT 3` (Software Breakpoint)
If a debugger is attached, it will typically catch the `INT 3` exception. If not, the program's own Structured Exception Handling (SEH) will catch it.

```cpp
#include <windows.h>

LONG WINAPI ExceptionHandler(EXCEPTION_POINTERS* ExceptionInfo) {
    if (ExceptionInfo->ExceptionRecord->ExceptionCode == EXCEPTION_BREAKPOINT) {
        std::cout << "[-] Breakpoint caught by SEH (No debugger or debugger ignored it)." << std::endl;
        return EXCEPTION_CONTINUE_EXECUTION;
    }
    return EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER;
}

void CheckInt3() {
    AddVectoredExceptionHandler(1, ExceptionHandler);

    __debugbreak(); // Compiles to int 3

    // If we reach here, the exception was handled by our handler, implying no debugger intercepted it first.
    // Note: Some debuggers pass exceptions to the program, making this check tricky.

    RemoveVectoredExceptionHandler(ExceptionHandler);
}
```

